Launch.en:
You should do implicit launches when possible, noting that it is almost always possible. The only time you need to do an explicit launch is if you need the code to execute with a different parent or caller than it normally would. This use-case is quite specialized. This function returns an object value of the newly started module. In general, variables that are listed in the final parameter spots are passed to the module as a value only. This means that if the launched module instance changes the value of one of the parameters, its value will not change outside of the scope of the module. If a launched module contains a Return statement it is will run as a subroutine, whether it is explicitly or implicitly launched. This is true even if the Return statement is in a state that does not get executed. In that case, the script that launches the sub-routine will stop its execution indefinitely, waiting for the sub-routine to return a value. If "myMod" is a subroutine, then in the statement, x = Launch("myMod", â¦); x will be set to the value returned by the subroutine's Return statement upon completion. Prior to execution of the Return statement, x will be invalid, unlike a module that is not a subroutine, which would set x to the object value of the launched module. A common syntactical problem with the use of the Launch function will result in two instances of a module running. The following example  shows the improper syntax [
  X Module;
  Y;
]
Launch(X, Self, Self); (assuming that "X" is declared as a module.) The problem here is the first parameter. As written above, the code will launch a module called "X", and use the return value from the launch (an object value) as the first parameter for Launch . This will result in two copies of the "X" module running. If you copy the module value into Y (ie Y = \X;), then Launch(Y, Self, Self) does not launch two copies. The correct syntax is: Launch("X", Self, Self); Use care in how you write a Launch statement. For example: X = Launch(Scope(<variable>, "Y", TRUE)... If it is unknown whether Y exists in the module pointed to by <variable> or if in fact <variable> is valid, then setting the ScopeLocal parameter to TRUE as shown, may help to avoid undesirable results. In the rare case that the module being launched is a child module of the caller's module, and if there are variables external to the module that the module itself will be required to alter, it is best to make them within the scope of Parent.

Launch.zh-cn:
您应该在可能的情况下进行隐式启动，并指出几乎总是可能的。您唯一需要进行明确启动的时间是，如果您需要与往常不同的父母或呼叫者执行的代码。这个用例非常专业。此功能返回新启动模块的对象值。通常，最终参数点中列出的变量仅作为值传递给模块。这意味着，如果启动的模块实例更改了一个参数的值，则其值将不会在模块范围之外变化。如果启动的模块包含返回语句，则将作为子例程运行，无论是明确还是隐式启动。即使返回语句处于未执行的状态，也是如此。在这种情况下，启动子规则的脚本将无限期地停止其执行，等待子列场返回值。如果“ mymod”是子例程，则在语句中，x =启动（“ mymod”，â€）; X将设置为由子例程完成后返回的返回语句返回的值。在执行返回语句之前，X将无效，与不是子例程的模块不同，该模块将将X设置为启动模块的对象值。使用启动功能的常见句法问题将导致两个模块运行的实例。以下示例显示了不当语法[
  X模块;
  y;
这是给出的
发射（x，self，self）; （假设“ x”被声明为模块。）这里的问题是第一个参数。如上所述，代码将启动一个称为“ X”的模块，并使用启动（对象值）中的返回值作为启动的第一个参数。这将导致运行“ X”模块的两个副本。如果将模块值复制到y（即y = \ x;）中，则启动（y，self，self）不会启动两个副本。正确的语法是：启动（“ x”，self，self）;在撰写启动语句的方式中使用护理。 For example: X = Launch(Scope(<variable>, "Y", TRUE)... If it is unknown whether Y exists in the module pointed to by <variable> or if in fact <variable> is valid, then setting the ScopeLocal parameter to TRUE as shown, may help to avoid undesirable results. In the rare case that the module being launched is a child module of the caller's module, and if there are variables external to the module that the模块本身将需要更改，最好将它们设置在父范围内。

